{"creativity-rating":5,"creativity-free-response":"It used physics to guide the plane instead of just the player.","originality-rating":5,"originality-free-response":"It felt different than other paper plane games since it uses wind to guide the plane instead of the player's flicks.","effectiveness-rating":5,"effectiveness-free-response":"The game was very enjoyable overall because the wind mechanic made guiding the paper plane feel interactive and skill based. Adjusting the wind to control the plane’s direction added strategy instead of just tapping or holding one button. The level of detail in how the plane reacted to stronger or weaker wind felt smooth and mostly realistic which made it satisfying when you successfully navigated obstacles.","authenticity-rating":4,"attention-check":3,"intentionality-rating":5,"authenticity-intentionality-free-response":"Authenticity. The game felt authentic because the wind mechanics and plane movement behaved in a believable and consistent way. The reactions to changes in airflow made sense and added to the realism of guiding a paper plane rather than feeling random or artificial.

Intentionality. The design choices seemed purposeful especially in how the wind influenced direction and difficulty. The obstacles and increasing challenge felt planned to test skill progression instead of being placed randomly.

Effort. It was clear that effort was put into the functionality and responsiveness of the controls. The smooth movement and interactive wind system showed attention to detail even if some areas like sensitivity balancing could be improved slightly."}

{"creativity-rating":2,"creativity-free-response":"The concept of a cube jumping across platforms to reach a green cube is very simple and straightforward which makes it feel less creative compared to more unique or thematic games. Platform jumping as a mechanic is extremely common and the objective of reaching a goal object is also widely used in many games. There was not much in terms of narrative theme or visual originality that made it stand out.","originality-free-response":"The game felt unoriginal because jumping from platform to platform to reach a goal cube is a very common mechanic in puzzle and platform games. The theme and aesthetics, simple cubes with a target, were minimal and didn’t add unique narrative or visual interest. There were no surprising elements or twists in gameplay, so it mostly felt predictable.","originality-rating":2,"effectiveness-rating":3,"effectiveness-free-response":"The game was moderately enjoyable because the controls and mechanics were simple and easy to understand, which made it accessible and straightforward to play. Successfully timing jumps to reach the green cube gave a small sense of satisfaction and accomplishment.

What worked well was the functionality, the cube responded predictably to player input, and the levels were clear in their objective. What was frustrating was the lack of variety or challenge beyond basic jumping; repeated platforming felt repetitive, and there were no unique visual or gameplay elements to keep it exciting over time. Overall it was functional and mildly entertaining, but somewhat basic.

","authenticity-rating":4,"attention-check":3,"intentionality-rating":5,"authenticity-intentionality-free-response":"The game felt somewhat authentic because, although the mechanics are common, it still had a clear goal and consistent design that suggested the developer created it with purpose rather than just copying another game. In terms of intentionality, the level layouts and goal of reaching the green cube showed planning, even if the design was simple. The effort was evident in the functional controls and clean presentation, though the minimal graphics and basic mechanics suggest moderate rather than extensive development effort."}
